00:02:55.690 --> 00:03:00.030
We ended last time looking
at the Schroedinger equation

00:03:00.030 --> 00:03:02.600
and seeing that the
Schroedinger equation could

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:06.100
be solved for a hydrogen
atom, giving information

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:08.300
about binding
energy, the binding

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:11.650
of the electron to
its nucleus, and also

00:03:11.650 --> 00:03:14.454
a wave function, which we
haven't talked about yet.

00:03:14.454 --> 00:03:15.870
So we're going to
continue talking

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:18.250
about this binding energy,
and then next week we're

00:03:18.250 --> 00:03:20.980
going to move into wave
functions, or orbitals.

00:03:20.980 --> 00:03:23.270
So the binding
energy that comes out

00:03:23.270 --> 00:03:25.270
of the Schroedinger
equation, no one

00:03:25.270 --> 00:03:27.100
should ever just believe things.

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:29.830
It looks fancy, but
does it really work?

00:03:29.830 --> 00:03:32.880
Is it really doing
this right estimation?

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:35.830
And again, it just came
out of Schroedinger's mind,

00:03:35.830 --> 00:03:39.310
so it's always nice to
verify that this equation is

00:03:39.310 --> 00:03:40.850
working pretty well.

00:03:40.850 --> 00:03:43.160
So today we're going
to talk about how

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:46.100
we were able to verify
that the binding energy

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:49.820
that the Schroedinger equation
was predicting actually

00:03:49.820 --> 00:03:52.170
agrees with experiment.

00:03:52.170 --> 00:03:55.640
So we're going to continue
talking about binding energies,

00:03:55.640 --> 00:03:58.680
then go on to the
verification, with a demo,

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:02.010
of how people were
able to show that there

00:04:02.010 --> 00:04:03.650
was good agreement here.

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:04.150
All right.

00:04:04.150 --> 00:04:06.700
So let's continue
with binding energies.

00:04:06.700 --> 00:04:09.680
So we're still talking about
the hydrogen atom and energy

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:14.360
levels, and we saw the last time
that the Schroedinger equation

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:17.560
could be derived
for a hydrogen atom

00:04:17.560 --> 00:04:20.810
such that the binding
energy, or e to the n,

00:04:20.810 --> 00:04:26.520
was equal to minus this Rydberg
constant, RH, over n squared

00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:29.600
were n is the principle
quantum number.

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:31.590
And so this is what
we saw last time,

00:04:31.590 --> 00:04:34.880
and now we have a graphical
depiction of this.

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:39.780
And you'll note that this is
a negative value over here.

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:44.200
So if n is 1 and we have
the principle quantum

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:49.280
number of one, we have
minus RH over one squared.

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:51.550
And so we just have
the negative value

00:04:51.550 --> 00:04:55.690
for the Rydberg constant,
2.18 times 10 to the minus

00:04:55.690 --> 00:04:57.760
18th joules.

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:01.240
And as we go up
here in energy, we

00:05:01.240 --> 00:05:04.440
would get to an energy of zero.

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:10.240
And if energy here is zero,
what must be true about n?

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:13.840
What kind of number is n here?

00:05:13.840 --> 00:05:15.860
Infinity, right.

00:05:15.860 --> 00:05:20.700
So if this is infinity,
that number goes to zero.

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:25.020
And so if the electron
is infinitely far away

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:28.550
from the nucleus, it's
basically a free electron.

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:30.920
It doesn't feel any
kind of attraction.

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:32.780
It's infinitely far away.

00:05:32.780 --> 00:05:36.130
Then your binding energy
would be zero, i.e.

00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:38.640
it's not bound,
and that would be

00:05:38.640 --> 00:05:42.180
true with this infinitely
far away distance.

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:46.750
And then in between the n
equals 1, 2n equals infinity,

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:49.790
we can use this equation
for the hydrogen atom

00:05:49.790 --> 00:05:54.280
to figure out what
these energy levels are.

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:57.990
So when we have the
n equals 2 state,

00:05:57.990 --> 00:06:02.670
it would be minus RH
over 2 squared, or 4,

00:06:02.670 --> 00:06:05.720
and so we can calculate
what that number is here,

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:12.160
minus 0.545 times 10 to
the minus 18th joules.

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:17.710
N equals 3 so we have
RH over 3 squared.

00:06:17.710 --> 00:06:20.610
We can do the math over here.

00:06:20.610 --> 00:06:26.280
4-- you get the idea--
minus RH over 4 squared,

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:30.510
and we have then over 5
squared, over 6 squared,

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:35.230
and you can see the energy, and
you can calculate the energy

00:06:35.230 --> 00:06:37.750
levels here.

00:06:37.750 --> 00:06:38.250
All right.

00:06:38.250 --> 00:06:44.800
So when you have an electron in
this n equals 1 state, that's

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:48.280
the lowest energy, it's
the most negative number,

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:51.010
and that's known as
the ground state.

00:06:51.010 --> 00:06:54.200
And when you have an electron
in this ground state,

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:59.100
that's the most stable
state for the hydrogen atom.

00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:03.070
So again, from these lower
ground state up to this state

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:04.810
here.

00:07:04.810 --> 00:07:07.300
Now we're going to
introduce another term which

00:07:07.300 --> 00:07:13.370
you'll hear a lot, and
this is ionization energy.

00:07:13.370 --> 00:07:16.110
So the ionization energy,
the amount of energy

00:07:16.110 --> 00:07:21.580
you need to put in to ionize
an atom or release an electron.

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:26.630
So the ionization energy of a
hydrogen atom in the nth state

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:29.380
is going to be equal
to the binding energy,

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:32.030
but the signs of these
are going to be different.

00:07:32.030 --> 00:07:36.480
So we have this equation where
binding energy equals minus IE,

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:39.140
the ionization energy.

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:43.900
So we talked about the fact that
the binding energy is negative,

00:07:43.900 --> 00:07:47.800
and the ionization energy
is always positive.

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:50.630
So for the binding energy, when
the binding energy is zero,

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:52.520
it means the
electron isn't bound.

00:07:52.520 --> 00:07:54.930
So a negative value
for binding energy

00:07:54.930 --> 00:07:57.230
means that the
electron's being held

00:07:57.230 --> 00:08:00.420
by the nucleus-- the
electron's bound.

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:02.980
For ionization energy,
that's the energy

00:08:02.980 --> 00:08:05.905
you need to add to the system
to release the electron,

00:08:05.905 --> 00:08:08.030
and you're always going to
need to add some energy,

00:08:08.030 --> 00:08:10.000
so that's a positive number.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.060
So when you think about
ionization energy,

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:14.770
it's a positive
number that you're

00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:17.570
going to be expecting there.

00:08:17.570 --> 00:08:20.940
Now we can consider
this same diagram,

00:08:20.940 --> 00:08:23.990
and we already talked
about these energy levels

00:08:23.990 --> 00:08:27.850
and now we can think about these
in terms of ionization energies

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:29.070
as well.

00:08:29.070 --> 00:08:31.030
So the difference
from this state,

00:08:31.030 --> 00:08:35.570
where energy is 0, to the
ground state down here,

00:08:35.570 --> 00:08:37.880
the ionization energy--
the energy that's

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:42.070
needed to ionize an electron
that's in n equals 1 here,

00:08:42.070 --> 00:08:45.290
is going to be equal
to minus the binding

00:08:45.290 --> 00:08:49.310
energy of that electron in
that n equals one state.

00:08:49.310 --> 00:08:52.290
So again here, it's
not too hard if you

00:08:52.290 --> 00:08:55.190
know this information
and this equation

00:08:55.190 --> 00:08:58.530
to figure out what the
ionization energy is.

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:01.960
So that's just, then, going
to be the positive value

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:03.540
of the binding energy.

00:09:03.540 --> 00:09:05.880
So binding energy
minus Rydberg's

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:11.310
constant here, 2.18 times
10 to the minus 18th joules.

00:09:11.310 --> 00:09:14.920
So the ionization energy,
then, for a hydrogen atom

00:09:14.920 --> 00:09:20.070
in the ground state is positive
2.180 times 10 to the minus

00:09:20.070 --> 00:09:20.760
18th.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:22.760
And I'm just going to try
to use the same number

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:24.320
of significant figures.

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:27.930
I always try to pay attention
to my significant figures.

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:28.430
All right.

00:09:28.430 --> 00:09:34.530
So we can do this again
for the n equals 2 state,

00:09:34.530 --> 00:09:38.480
or the first excited state.

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:41.040
So here's the n equals 2 state.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:44.290
So now we're going to be talking
about this differential energy

00:09:44.290 --> 00:09:46.970
here.

00:09:46.970 --> 00:09:50.780
So the ionization
energy for an electron

00:09:50.780 --> 00:09:53.120
in this first excited state.

00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:57.080
Again, that will be ionization
energy equals minus the binding

00:09:57.080 --> 00:10:00.490
energy for that state,
and so that's going to be,

00:10:00.490 --> 00:10:02.640
then, the positive value here.

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:09.110
So the binding energy was minus,
if we change this to-- this

00:10:09.110 --> 00:10:14.910
is 18.5 to the 18, or 5.0
to the minus 19th joules.

00:10:14.910 --> 00:10:18.190
Try to keep the significant
figures the same.

00:10:18.190 --> 00:10:18.690
All right.

00:10:18.690 --> 00:10:21.155
So why don't you
give this a try now

00:10:21.155 --> 00:10:23.170
and we'll have a
clicker question.

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:14.940
OK.

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:15.606
10 more seconds.

00:11:34.870 --> 00:11:38.440
A very long one second.

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:40.814
OK.

00:11:40.814 --> 00:11:41.314
Interesting.

00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:51.990
So maybe you can talk to
your neighbor and someone can

00:11:51.990 --> 00:11:53.590
tell me what the trick is here.

00:12:10.900 --> 00:12:11.440
OK.

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:14.530
We have someone who is going
to tell us what the trick is.

00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:21.560
AUDIENCE: The ground
state is n equals one,

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:24.830
and from there, the
excited states go up one.

00:12:24.830 --> 00:12:27.900
So the first excited
state is n equals 2,

00:12:27.900 --> 00:12:31.220
and then the third one
will be n equals 4.

00:12:31.220 --> 00:12:33.760
And since you're looking
for the ionization energy,

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:37.950
you go to the energy
for n equals 4,

00:12:37.950 --> 00:12:42.810
and you multiply by negative
one, which is 40.14 10

00:12:42.810 --> 00:12:45.120
to the negative 18th.

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:46.430
PROFESSOR: Great.

00:12:46.430 --> 00:12:49.520
Yeah, so let's see what I have.

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:51.086
I need to get some more stuff.

00:12:51.086 --> 00:12:52.310
Sorry.

00:12:52.310 --> 00:12:52.900
OK.

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:56.481
So the trick.

00:12:56.481 --> 00:12:57.480
It's not a hard problem.

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:00.660
You just had to figure out what
the third excited state meant,

00:13:00.660 --> 00:13:03.610
so once you've figured
that out, it was

00:13:03.610 --> 00:13:05.350
pretty easy to get it right.

00:13:05.350 --> 00:13:06.120
OK.

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:07.930
So keep that in mind.

00:13:07.930 --> 00:13:10.190
Now that you've potentially
made that mistake,

00:13:10.190 --> 00:13:12.600
you will not make
that one again.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:13.460
All right.

00:13:13.460 --> 00:13:17.540
So now we can think about this
also in more general terms--

00:13:17.540 --> 00:13:19.630
only slightly more
general terms,

00:13:19.630 --> 00:13:28.660
frankly-- which is to consider,
for other one electron ions,

00:13:28.660 --> 00:13:31.180
we can have a more
general equation.

00:13:31.180 --> 00:13:34.840
So we had, for
the hydrogen atom,

00:13:34.840 --> 00:13:39.640
the binding energy, En, is minus
Rydberg's constant, RH, over

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:40.560
n squared.

00:13:40.560 --> 00:13:45.260
And now I've added z squared,
which is the atomic number.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:48.670
And for hydrogen, it's
1, so it wasn't around.

00:13:48.670 --> 00:13:50.330
We didn't need it before.

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:55.470
But we can consider other ions
that also have one electron.

00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:59.370
They will also work
with this equation.

00:13:59.370 --> 00:14:02.530
So there's a couple of things
that kind of fall out of this.

00:14:02.530 --> 00:14:06.140
One, that an electron is
going to be bound more weakly

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:12.150
when n is a big number here, and
so that makes sense from what

00:14:12.150 --> 00:14:14.500
we were looking at before.

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:17.130
And that an electron
is also going

00:14:17.130 --> 00:14:21.254
to be bound more
tightly when z is big,

00:14:21.254 --> 00:14:23.670
and we haven't really talked
about that because we've just

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:25.970
been talking about
the hydrogen atom,

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:28.450
and so it always has the same z.

00:14:28.450 --> 00:14:30.280
But if you have a
different z, you're

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:34.100
going to have a bigger
positively charged nucleus,

00:14:34.100 --> 00:14:37.490
and so it makes sense that
you would then have a tighter

00:14:37.490 --> 00:14:39.200
bonding electron.

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:39.970
All right.

00:14:39.970 --> 00:14:42.560
So you might think, what
are other things that

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:46.020
have just one electron that
this is going to apply to?

00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:47.450
And so far, of
course, we've just

00:14:47.450 --> 00:14:49.730
been talking about
our friend, hydrogen,

00:14:49.730 --> 00:14:52.720
that has its one
electron and z equals 1.

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:57.400
But we have ions that can
also have one electron.

00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:02.510
So helium plus, and it has a z
of 2, but when it's helium plus

00:15:02.510 --> 00:15:05.200
it only has one electron.

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:09.470
Lithium, plus 2, also
only has one electron,

00:15:09.470 --> 00:15:12.730
and it has a z of three.

00:15:12.730 --> 00:15:17.570
And then what about something
that's a one electron

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:21.250
system with a plus 64.

00:15:21.250 --> 00:15:23.840
Without looking at your
periodic table, what does

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:26.520
the z have to be here?

00:15:26.520 --> 00:15:27.590
Yeah.

00:15:27.590 --> 00:15:29.330
So, 65.

00:15:29.330 --> 00:15:31.450
So in working these
kinds of problems,

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:36.410
if you're talking about a
one electron ion or atom

00:15:36.410 --> 00:15:39.280
and it's not hydrogen,
don't forget about z.

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:41.546
And we need to have
that in our equation.

00:15:43.990 --> 00:15:44.490
All right.

00:15:44.490 --> 00:15:49.860
So talking about these
binding energies now,

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:51.650
out of the
Schroedinger equation,

00:15:51.650 --> 00:15:53.960
you can calculate
ionization energies

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:55.280
if you know the binding energy.

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:56.990
All of this is
good, but how do we

00:15:56.990 --> 00:15:59.660
know that we can trust
the Schroedinger equation,

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:02.460
that equations
really are working?

00:16:02.460 --> 00:16:04.790
So the way that they
figured this out

00:16:04.790 --> 00:16:08.630
is from experiment, and
particularly, experimentally

00:16:08.630 --> 00:16:12.830
figuring out what the energy
levels were, and thinking,

00:16:12.830 --> 00:16:15.380
does this match with the
Schroedinger equation?

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:20.240
So they were able to use photon
emission to be able to do this.

00:16:20.240 --> 00:16:24.720
So let's consider what
photon emission is,

00:16:24.720 --> 00:16:28.570
and then we're going to prove
that this equation that I've

00:16:28.570 --> 00:16:31.430
been showing you actually holds.

00:16:31.430 --> 00:16:35.570
So photon emission,
this is a situation

00:16:35.570 --> 00:16:38.320
that occurs when
you have an electron

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:44.590
going from a higher energy
initial state going to a lower

00:16:44.590 --> 00:16:46.660
energy state.

00:16:46.660 --> 00:16:50.070
And as it goes from
this high energy state

00:16:50.070 --> 00:16:54.320
to the low energy state, there's
a difference between these two

00:16:54.320 --> 00:16:56.870
energy states,
delta E, and that's

00:16:56.870 --> 00:16:59.710
going to be equal
to the higher energy

00:16:59.710 --> 00:17:03.940
initial state minus the
energy in the final state.

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:07.670
So there's this difference in
energy between the two states,

00:17:07.670 --> 00:17:12.750
and the photon that gets
emitted when this energy

00:17:12.750 --> 00:17:17.310
transition happens has the
same energy as the difference

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:18.359
between those.

00:17:18.359 --> 00:17:23.140
So the energy of the emitted
photon is also delta E.

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:28.079
So you emit all of that energy
as you have that change.

00:17:28.079 --> 00:17:33.310
So the difference here-- we
can consider an actual case

00:17:33.310 --> 00:17:36.360
where we're going from
an energy difference of n

00:17:36.360 --> 00:17:41.660
equals 6 to an energy
level of an equals 2,

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:44.880
and we can think about what
the energy difference is

00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:49.060
between these two and we can
just write that equation out.

00:17:49.060 --> 00:17:55.940
So the initial energy, the
electron started at n equals 6,

00:17:55.940 --> 00:17:58.090
the energy of the
n equals 6 state,

00:17:58.090 --> 00:18:02.130
and it goes to the energy
of the n equals 2 state.

00:18:02.130 --> 00:18:08.040
So energy n equals 6
minus energy n equals 2.

00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:09.360
All right.

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:11.690
So of course if you
know energy, you

00:18:11.690 --> 00:18:15.300
can know a lot of other
things about the photon.

00:18:15.300 --> 00:18:20.120
So you can calculate frequency
of that emitted photon.

00:18:20.120 --> 00:18:23.410
So again, we have our
energy difference here

00:18:23.410 --> 00:18:27.170
and we can then solve
for the frequency

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:31.040
of the emitted photon, which is
equal to the energy difference.

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:35.070
That energy, divided
by Planck's constant,

00:18:35.070 --> 00:18:39.150
and you could also write
it out, the initial energy

00:18:39.150 --> 00:18:41.780
minus the final energy over h.

00:18:41.780 --> 00:18:43.900
All of these are
equivalent things.

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:46.630
And when you know
frequency, we're

00:18:46.630 --> 00:18:50.290
talking about light here, so you
can calculate the wavelength.

00:18:52.890 --> 00:18:55.850
So let's think now about
what we might expect

00:18:55.850 --> 00:18:58.520
in terms of frequencies
and wavelengths,

00:18:58.520 --> 00:19:02.470
depending on the energy
difference between the two

00:19:02.470 --> 00:19:04.790
different states.

00:19:04.790 --> 00:19:08.490
So here, if we think
first about this electron

00:19:08.490 --> 00:19:12.700
with the purple line, we have
a large energy difference

00:19:12.700 --> 00:19:16.300
here between this
state and this state

00:19:16.300 --> 00:19:20.530
down here, between n
equals 5 to n equals 1.

00:19:20.530 --> 00:19:23.500
So when we have a large
difference in energy,

00:19:23.500 --> 00:19:26.080
what do we expect
about the frequency

00:19:26.080 --> 00:19:27.910
of the emitted photon?

00:19:27.910 --> 00:19:32.010
Is it going to be a high
frequency or low frequency?

00:19:32.010 --> 00:19:33.010
High.

00:19:33.010 --> 00:19:33.910
Yep.

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:36.840
So large energy, high frequency.

00:19:36.840 --> 00:19:40.150
And so then what would be
true about the wavelength

00:19:40.150 --> 00:19:42.780
of that emitted photon?

00:19:42.780 --> 00:19:43.920
Short.

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:46.020
Right.

00:19:46.020 --> 00:19:49.800
Now if we had a small
difference, say n equals 3 to n

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:53.400
equals 1, which is a smaller
difference in energy, what's

00:19:53.400 --> 00:19:56.421
true about the frequency here?

00:19:56.421 --> 00:19:56.920
Right.

00:19:56.920 --> 00:19:58.120
Low frequency.

00:19:58.120 --> 00:20:00.150
And wavelength?

00:20:00.150 --> 00:20:03.050
Right, long wavelength.

00:20:03.050 --> 00:20:04.850
Right.

