to see it.

00:25:43.870 --> 00:25:51.420
So J.J. Balmer, in 1885,
reported seeing these colors,

00:25:51.420 --> 00:25:55.180
and he wanted to calculate
the frequencies of the lights

00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:58.010
that you were seeing
emitted from this.

00:25:58.010 --> 00:26:01.420
And so he did calculate
the frequency,

00:26:01.420 --> 00:26:04.470
and then he tried to figure out
the mathematical relationship

00:26:04.470 --> 00:26:06.440
between the different
frequencies of light

00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:07.800
that he was observing.

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:12.660
And he found that the
frequency equaled 3.29 times 10

00:26:12.660 --> 00:26:17.610
to the 15th per second,
times 1 over 4 minus 1

00:26:17.610 --> 00:26:23.540
over some number, n, where
n was either 3, 4, or 5.

00:26:23.540 --> 00:26:26.390
And he really didn't understand
what the significance of this

00:26:26.390 --> 00:26:28.320
was, but it was pretty.

00:26:28.320 --> 00:26:30.760
You had hydrogen in
this sealed tube,

00:26:30.760 --> 00:26:35.780
and there were colors that came
off, and they had frequencies.

00:26:35.780 --> 00:26:39.370
So that's kind of where that
stood for a little while.

00:26:39.370 --> 00:26:43.080
So now let's think about what
those different colored lights

00:26:43.080 --> 00:26:44.600
were due to.

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:51.070
So we have here energy
levels, and the transitions

00:26:51.070 --> 00:26:56.000
that we were observing
are all going to be n

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:58.550
equals 2 final state.

00:26:58.550 --> 00:27:02.110
And we can think about why you
didn't see any transitions to n

00:27:02.110 --> 00:27:02.680
equals one.

00:27:02.680 --> 00:27:03.560
Think about that.

00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:05.791
We'll come back to
that in a minute.

00:27:05.791 --> 00:27:07.540
But there were these
different transitions

00:27:07.540 --> 00:27:12.180
that were being observed
from 3 to 2, 4 to 2, 5 to 2,

00:27:12.180 --> 00:27:13.540
and 6 to 2.

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:18.340
So now let's think about which
colors-- which wavelengths--

00:27:18.340 --> 00:27:21.730
are due to which
of the transitions.

00:27:21.730 --> 00:27:25.740
So for the red one,
what do you think?

00:27:25.740 --> 00:27:29.890
3, 4, or 5 transitioned to 2?

00:27:29.890 --> 00:27:31.300
3.

00:27:31.300 --> 00:27:32.520
It is 3.

00:27:32.520 --> 00:27:36.420
And you could think about that
in terms of the smaller energy.

00:27:36.420 --> 00:27:39.210
That's the smallest
energy, so that

00:27:39.210 --> 00:27:43.470
would be a low frequency
and a long wavelength.

00:27:43.470 --> 00:27:46.540
So the one with the longest
wavelength-- and red

00:27:46.540 --> 00:27:48.820
is the longest
wavelength-- so that

00:27:48.820 --> 00:27:55.160
must be the transition from an
initial n of 3 to n equal 2.

00:27:55.160 --> 00:27:59.700
And then we can fill in the
rest, so this one over here

00:27:59.700 --> 00:28:03.850
must have been n equals 4 to 2.

00:28:03.850 --> 00:28:09.990
This one here, then, would
be the blue, n equals 5 to 2.

00:28:09.990 --> 00:28:15.240
And then the purple or indigo
at the end, n equals 6 to n

00:28:15.240 --> 00:28:16.810
equals 2.

00:28:16.810 --> 00:28:19.970
So they saw these
four colors, there

00:28:19.970 --> 00:28:22.040
were these different
transitions,

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:24.720
and so then, now,
we can calculate

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:27.680
what the frequencies
of these are and think

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:32.040
about this, then, in terms
of Schroedinger's equation

00:28:32.040 --> 00:28:37.090
and test Schroedinger's equation
to see if it predicts this.

00:28:37.090 --> 00:28:39.740
So we can calculate
the frequency, then,

00:28:39.740 --> 00:28:43.320
of the emitted
photons, and we had

00:28:43.320 --> 00:28:48.860
frequency equals the initial
energy minus the final energy

00:28:48.860 --> 00:28:54.940
state, or this delta E,
over Planck's constant.

00:28:54.940 --> 00:28:57.350
And from the
Schroedinger equation,

00:28:57.350 --> 00:29:01.500
we know about what these energy
levels are from Schroedinger.

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:05.090
And this is, again, for
hydrogen, so z equals 1, so z

00:29:05.090 --> 00:29:06.360
isn't shown.

00:29:06.360 --> 00:29:11.530
We have the binding energy
equals minus RH, Rydberg

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:14.080
constant over n squared.

00:29:14.080 --> 00:29:17.200
And now we can put these
equations together.

00:29:17.200 --> 00:29:22.200
So we can substitute these
energies in using these,

00:29:22.200 --> 00:29:24.920
and so we can do that here.

00:29:24.920 --> 00:29:29.680
We'll pull out Planck's
constant, so 1 over h.

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:38.980
And then we can substitute in
minus RH over the initial n

00:29:38.980 --> 00:29:47.820
level squared minus minus
RH over the final n squared.

00:29:47.820 --> 00:29:51.180
And we can also simplify
this a little more,

00:29:51.180 --> 00:29:57.560
pull out RH over here, and now
we just have 1 over the final--

00:29:57.560 --> 00:29:59.920
we have minus a minus,
so we've rearranged

00:29:59.920 --> 00:30:06.950
this-- 1 over n final squared
minus 1 over n initial squared.

00:30:06.950 --> 00:30:10.510
And we have an
equation that solves

00:30:10.510 --> 00:30:15.490
for the frequency in terms of
Rydberg, Planck's constant,

00:30:15.490 --> 00:30:20.450
and what the principle quantum
numbers are, what n is.

00:30:20.450 --> 00:30:22.380
So let's look at
this a little more.

00:30:22.380 --> 00:30:28.470
Now remember, this is all
going to n final of 2,

00:30:28.470 --> 00:30:31.720
and so we can put that
equation up here again.

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:35.290
So when this is
2, 2 squared is 4.

00:30:35.290 --> 00:30:37.960
And if you remember
back, Balmer had

00:30:37.960 --> 00:30:41.430
a 4-- had this part
of the expression--

00:30:41.430 --> 00:30:44.640
but he had a strange
number over here

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:47.470
that he experimentally
determined.

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:51.300
But if you take RH and divide
by Planck's constant, Rydberg

00:30:51.300 --> 00:30:53.420
constant divided
by Planck's, you

00:30:53.420 --> 00:30:56.980
get that number that
Balmer had found back

00:30:56.980 --> 00:31:03.710
in 1885-- 3.29 times 10
to the 15th per second.

00:31:03.710 --> 00:31:08.330
So when we plug in the values
from Schroedinger's equations,

00:31:08.330 --> 00:31:11.300
you come up with the
experimentally determined

00:31:11.300 --> 00:31:13.830
values for frequencies,
or wavelength,

00:31:13.830 --> 00:31:15.480
of the emitted light.

00:31:15.480 --> 00:31:17.210
And of course,
from the frequency,

00:31:17.210 --> 00:31:19.100
you can calculate
the wavelength,

00:31:19.100 --> 00:31:22.560
and the wavelengths that
were observed experimentally

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:25.280
agreed with the wavelength
you would calculate

00:31:25.280 --> 00:31:29.020
from the Schroedinger's
equation to one part, n times 10

00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:29.900
to the 8th.

00:31:29.900 --> 00:31:33.070
So the agreement was
absolutely amazing.

00:31:33.070 --> 00:31:34.950
So Schroedinger's
equation, which

00:31:34.950 --> 00:31:38.280
was taking into account
the wavelike properties

00:31:38.280 --> 00:31:41.090
of the electrons,
were able to predict,

00:31:41.090 --> 00:31:43.890
for a hydrogen atom,
what wavelengths

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:47.980
you should see emitted in
that hydrogen atom spectra.

00:31:47.980 --> 00:31:50.330
So this was really exciting.

00:31:50.330 --> 00:31:52.630
Schroedinger
equation was working,

00:31:52.630 --> 00:31:55.700
we had a way of
describing the behavior

00:31:55.700 --> 00:31:58.300
that we were observing
for these electrons,

00:31:58.300 --> 00:32:00.730
and that was really incredible.

00:32:00.730 --> 00:32:03.940
And I think Balmer should
get a lot of credit as well

00:32:03.940 --> 00:32:05.450
for all of this.

00:32:05.450 --> 00:32:07.720
And the people who were doing
these early experiments,

00:32:07.720 --> 00:32:09.090
they didn't know
what it was meaning,

00:32:09.090 --> 00:32:11.200
but they were coming up
with the data that allowed

00:32:11.200 --> 00:32:13.500
to test theories later on.

00:32:13.500 --> 00:32:14.000
OK.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:18.760
So this was a series
going to a final n of 2,

00:32:18.760 --> 00:32:20.630
and so we have
the Balmer series.

00:32:20.630 --> 00:32:24.620
That was the visible
series that we were seeing.

00:32:24.620 --> 00:32:30.701
So what about, why wasn't
anything going to n equals 1?

00:32:30.701 --> 00:32:31.950
And that's a clicker question.

