00:38:16.760 --> 00:38:19.360
look at some pretty colors.

00:38:19.360 --> 00:38:23.460
So in this case now, we can
calculate frequency again,

00:38:23.460 --> 00:38:26.270
but our equation is a
little bit different.

00:38:26.270 --> 00:38:30.390
So we have the Rydberg constant
and Planck's constant again,

00:38:30.390 --> 00:38:37.220
but now we have 1 over initial
n squared minus final n squared,

00:38:37.220 --> 00:38:41.160
and so this term should
be a positive term.

00:38:41.160 --> 00:38:43.623
We should be getting out
a positive frequency.

00:38:46.350 --> 00:38:50.020
So if I take this again
and put it up here,

00:38:50.020 --> 00:38:51.900
you want to think about
whether, if you're

00:38:51.900 --> 00:38:55.040
talking about
absorption or emission,

00:38:55.040 --> 00:38:59.310
that's what's telling you if the
energy is being gained or lost.

00:38:59.310 --> 00:39:02.171
So you're not going to have
negative frequencies in one

00:39:02.171 --> 00:39:02.670
case.

00:39:02.670 --> 00:39:05.610
You're going to be
absorbing the light

00:39:05.610 --> 00:39:09.980
of a particular frequency, or
emitting light of a frequency.

00:39:09.980 --> 00:39:12.297
So pay attention
to your equations,

00:39:12.297 --> 00:39:14.130
and think about whether
your answer actually

00:39:14.130 --> 00:39:16.040
make sense when you do them.

00:39:16.040 --> 00:39:17.810
And again, all
